        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>&ldquo;The real solution is you,&rdquo; Gore said to the hundreds of students in attendance. &ldquo;You are capable of making a tremendous difference.... But to those who are closer to my generation, they need us to take leadership.&rdquo;</p>
<p>After the lecture, some students said they enjoyed the speech and appreciated the passion with which Gore described climate change and its possible solutions.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I liked how he framed it as a moral issue, because we&rsquo;re beyond the debate about whether it&rsquo;s happening, and we need to go and really look at the moral perspective,&rdquo; said Allison Herren, a masters student in environmental management at the Nicholas School.</p>
<p>Nicholas School Dean Bill Chameides said he found Gore especially entertaining and passionate about the topic. Chameides spoke briefly at the start of the event before Democratic state Sen. and Board of Trustees Chair Dan Blue, Law &rsquo;73, introduced the former vice president.</p>
<p>&ldquo;I was blown away,&rdquo; Chameides said in an interview after the event. &ldquo;He does a great job of getting into people&rsquo;s heads and connecting with them.... &nbsp;Clearly he feels very passionately that this is an ethical choice.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But not all of those gathered on the Chapel Quadrangle after the event agreed with Gore&rsquo;s positions on climate change. A group of about eight individuals protested the lecture with signs and posters. The group was not affiliated with the University, nor were they invited by a student group, said Vice President for Student Affairs Larry Moneta.</p>

